[Functors and matrix indexing](https://www.learncpp.com/cpp-tutorial/99-overloading-the-parenthesis-operator/) are, to my knowledge, the most common use cases.

**Matrix Indexing**  
For a matrix class, you can do something like this:

```
Matrix3x3 A;
A(1,2) = 2;
```

The main reason that parentheses are used instead of brackets in this case is that the brackets operator only accepts one argument while the parentheses operator accepts multiple arguments.

**Functor**  
If you want an object to act as a function that can also store information, you can do:

```
Accumulator accumulate;
for(int i=0; i&lt;20; ++i)
    accumulate(i);
std::cout &lt;&lt; accumulate.sum &lt;&lt; std::endl;
```

In C++, you will also often encounter functors for [comparator objects](https://thispointer.com/c-how-to-sort-a-list-of-objects-with-custom-comparator-or-lambda-function/), even though they do not store information.

